{"title_page": "Zarah Sultana", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| birth_place = [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], [[England]]\n| nationality = British\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Birmingham]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| honorific_suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]]\n| termstart = 12 December 2019\n| termend = \n| predecessor = [[Jim Cunningham (politician)|Jim Cunningham]]\n| majority = 401 (0.9%)\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|31 October 1993|df=yes}}\n}}\n'''Zarah Sultana''' (born 31 October 1993) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nSultana was born on 31 October 1993<ref name=\"LabourList\" /><ref>{{cite tweet|last=Sultana|first=Zarah|title=Way to overshadow my birthday guys||user=zarahsultana|number=1116117458941771777|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> in the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] and raised in [[Lozells]], [[Birmingham]]. She is a Muslim. Her grandfather moved to the West Midlands in the 1960s from [[Azad Kashmir]], Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/601112-for-the-first-time-ever-british-parliament-has-more-female-muslim-mps-than-male-muslim-members|title=For the first time ever, British parliament has more female Muslim MPs than male Muslim members &#124; World &#124; thenews.com.pk &#124;}}</ref> \n\nShe attended [[Holte School]], a non-selective community school.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/general-election-candidates-qa-coventry-17317459|title=Coventry South election candidate in the spotlight|last=Stretton|first=Rachel|date=3 December 2019|work=Coventry Telegraph|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> Sultana then studied at [[King Edward VI Handsworth School]], a grammar school, for sixth form.<ref name=\":0\"/> \n\nShe joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 2011, following the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|coalition government]]'s decision to increase tuition fees to \u00a39,000.<ref name=Vice/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gal-dem.com/zarah-sultana-mp-thatcherism-climate-student-debt-labour/|title='The future is ours \u2013 it has to be': MP Zarah Sultana sets out her mission for change|publisher=gal-dem|date=23 January 2020|last=Sultana|first=Zarah|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> While at university, Sultana was elected to the National Executive Council of both [[Young Labour (UK)|Young Labour]] and the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]].<ref name=\"JC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/exclusive-labour-parliamentary-candidate-said-she-would-celebrate-deaths-of-blair-netanyahu-1.491027|title=Exclusive: Labour MP hopeful said she would 'celebrate' deaths of Blair, Netanyahu|work=The Jewish Chronicle|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n\nSultana was listed fifth of seven among the Labour candidates for the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament elections]] in the [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands constituency]], meaning that she would be elected if Labour received enough votes in the region to receive 5 MEPs. She was not elected, as Labour won 1 MEP in the constituency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48081683|title=2019 European elections: List of candidates for the West Midlands{{!}} BBC News|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/crjeqkdevwvt/the-uks-european-elections-2019|title=The UK's European elections 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 October 2019, Sultana was selected as the Labour candidate for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]]<ref name=LabourList/> after Labour MP [[Jim Cunningham (politician)|Jim Cunningham]] announced that he would stand down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://members.parliament.uk/member/308/career|title=Mr Jim Cunningham|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref> Her campaign was backed by [[Unite the Union]], [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]], the [[Fire Brigades Union]], the [[Communication Workers Union (United Kingdom)|Communication Workers Union]] and [[Bakers, Food and Allied Workers' Union]]. She is on the left-wing of the party.<ref name=\"LabourList\">{{cite web |last1=Rodgers |first1=Sienna |title=Labour organiser Zarah Sultana picked to fight Coventry South |website=LabourList |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/11/labour-organiser-zarah-sultana-picked-to-fight-coventry-south/ |date=1 November 2019 |accessdate=}}</ref> Sultana was elected as MP for Coventry South in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], with a majority of 401.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000651|title=Coventry South|accessdate=17 January 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign, ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'' reported that in 2015, while she was a student, Sultana made social media posts from a subsequently deleted account which implied that she would celebrate the deaths of former Labour prime minister [[Tony Blair]], Israeli prime minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] and former US president [[George W. Bush]] and she supported \"violent resistance\" by Palestinians.<ref name=JC/> Sultana apologised for the posts and stated that she no longer held those views and \"wrote them out of frustration rather than any malice\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-50292235|title=Labour Coventry South candidate Zarah Sultana apologises for 'celebrate deaths' post|publisher=BBC News|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/house/house-magazine/108577/class-2019-meet-new-mps|publisher=Politics Home|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020|last=Bond|first=Daniel|title=Class of 2019: Meet the new MPs}}</ref> The Labour Party re-interviewed her as a consequence of the posts, and she remained the candidate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/coventry-labour-candidate-faces-re-17217042|work=Coventry Telegraph|title=Coventry Labour candidate faces 're-interview' over tweets|date=18 November 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020|last=Stretton|first=Rachel}}</ref> Subsequent to her election, a further social media post made by Sultana in 2015 was reported in which she stated that students supporting [[Zionism]] were \"advocating a racist ideology...champion[ing] a state created through [[ethnic cleansing]] ...[[apartheid]] and [[war crimes]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-zarah-sultana-told-jewish-student-privilege-allowed-them-to-argue-peaceful-solution-to-i-1.495607|title=Labour MP Zarah Sultana told student that 'privilege' allowed them to argue for Middle East peace|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=24 January 2020|work=Jewish Chronicle|accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn her maiden speech, she decried what she called \"40 years of [[Thatcherism]]\", criticised the effects of [[United Kingdom government austerity programme|austerity]], and voiced her support for a [[Green_New_Deal#In_the_UK|Green New Deal]] to combat climate change.<ref name=Vice>{{cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/7kz8p9/zarah-sultana-mp-labour-maiden-speech-interview|publisher=Vice|title=Zarah Sultana MP: 'When I See Conservatives, I Think About All the Harm They've Caused'|last=Segalov|first=Michael|date=23 January 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://coventryobserver.co.uk/news/sultana-breaks-convention-in-maiden-speech-to-the-commons/|work=Coventry Observer|title=New Coventry MP Sultana, 26, uses first Commons speech to fire broadside for 'my generation'|date=16 January 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> She joined the [[Socialist Campaign Group]] shortly after being elected<ref>{{cite tweet|user=zarahsultana|number=1220108818484539392|title=Proud to be in the Socialist Campaign Group meeting today for its official endorsement of @RLong_Bailey for Leader and @RichardBurgon for Deputy Leader. Now let's get these socialists elected! pic.twitter.com/2wndXTOOyU|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> and in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]], nominated [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] for leader and [[Richard Burgon]] for [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|deputy leader]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/rolling-list-mp-mep-nominations-for-labour-leadership-candidates/|publisher=LabourList|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=17 January 2020|title=Rolling list: MP/MEP nominations for Labour leadership candidates}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/rolling-list-mp-mep-nominations-for-labour-deputy-leadership-candidates/|publisher=LabourList|date=8 January 2020|title=Rolling list: MP/MEP nominations for Labour deputy leadership candidates|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2020, Sultana was appointed as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Dan Carden]], the [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=zarahsultana |number=1222165789165273091 |date=28 January 2020 |title= I'm excited to join the Shadow International Development team, as @DanCardenMP's Parliamentary Private Secretary! The struggle to build a sustainable world for all \u2013 not just the super-rich \u2013 is close to my heart. That's the role Britain should be playing on the global stage.}}</ref> She was removed from this role in a subsequent reshuffle under [[Keir Starmer]]. <ref>https://labourlist.org/2020/04/shadow-ministers-appointed-as-starmer-completes-frontbench/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=4786 |publicwhip=Zarah_Sultana |theywork=zarah_sultana}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Cunningham (politician)|Jim Cunningham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br />for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]]|years=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{West Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sultana, Zarah}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:English people of Azad Kashmiri descent]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of Parliament for Coventry]]\n[[Category:Muslim socialists]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Edward VI Handsworth]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{short description|British politician}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n| birth_place = [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]], [[England]]\n| nationality = British\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[University of Birmingham]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| honorific_suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]]\n| termstart = 12 December 2019\n| termend = \n| predecessor = [[Jim Cunningham (politician)|Jim Cunningham]]\n| majority = 401 (0.9%)\n| image = \n| caption = \n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|31 October 1993|df=yes}}\n}}\n'''Zarah Sultana''' (born 31 October 1993) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician who has been the [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nSultana was born on 31 October 1993<ref name=\"LabourList\" /><ref>{{cite tweet|last=Sultana|first=Zarah|title=Way to overshadow my birthday guys||user=zarahsultana|number=1116117458941771777|date=11 April 2019|accessdate=15 January 2020}}</ref> in the [[West Midlands (county)|West Midlands]] and raised in [[Lozells]], [[Birmingham]]. She is a Muslim. Her grandfather moved to the West Midlands in the 1960s from [[Azad Kashmir]], Pakistan.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thenews.com.pk/latest/601112-for-the-first-time-ever-british-parliament-has-more-female-muslim-mps-than-male-muslim-members|title=For the first time ever, British parliament has more female Muslim MPs than male Muslim members &#124; World &#124; thenews.com.pk &#124;}}</ref> \n\nShe attended [[Holte School]], a non-selective community school.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/general-election-candidates-qa-coventry-17317459|title=Coventry South election candidate in the spotlight|last=Stretton|first=Rachel|date=3 December 2019|work=Coventry Telegraph|accessdate=15 December 2019}}</ref> Sultana then studied at [[King Edward VI Handsworth School]], a grammar school, for sixth form.<ref name=\":0\"/> \n\nShe joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 2011, following the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|coalition government]]'s decision to increase tuition fees to \u00a39,000.<ref name=Vice/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://gal-dem.com/zarah-sultana-mp-thatcherism-climate-student-debt-labour/|title='The future is ours \u2013 it has to be': MP Zarah Sultana sets out her mission for change|publisher=gal-dem|date=23 January 2020|last=Sultana|first=Zarah|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> While at university, Sultana was elected to the National Executive Council of both [[Young Labour (UK)|Young Labour]] and the [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]].<ref name=\"JC\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/exclusive-labour-parliamentary-candidate-said-she-would-celebrate-deaths-of-blair-netanyahu-1.491027|title=Exclusive: Labour MP hopeful said she would 'celebrate' deaths of Blair, Netanyahu|work=The Jewish Chronicle|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\n\nSultana was listed fifth of seven among the Labour candidates for the [[2019 European Parliament election in the United Kingdom|2019 European Parliament elections]] in the [[West Midlands (European Parliament constituency)|West Midlands constituency]], meaning that she would be elected if Labour received enough votes in the region to receive 5 MEPs. She was not elected, as Labour won 1 MEP in the constituency.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-48081683|title=2019 European elections: List of candidates for the West Midlands{{!}} BBC News|website=www.bbc.co.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-04-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/topics/crjeqkdevwvt/the-uks-european-elections-2019|title=The UK's European elections 2019|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 October 2019, Sultana was selected as the Labour candidate for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]]<ref name=LabourList/> after Labour MP [[Jim Cunningham (politician)|Jim Cunningham]] announced that he would stand down.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://members.parliament.uk/member/308/career|title=Mr Jim Cunningham|publisher=parliament.uk|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref> Her campaign was backed by [[Unite the Union]], [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]], the [[Fire Brigades Union]], the [[Communication Workers Union (United Kingdom)|Communication Workers Union]] and [[Bakers, Food and Allied Workers' Union]]. She is on the left-wing of the party.<ref name=\"LabourList\">{{cite web |last1=Rodgers |first1=Sienna |title=Labour organiser Zarah Sultana picked to fight Coventry South |website=LabourList |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/11/labour-organiser-zarah-sultana-picked-to-fight-coventry-south/ |date=1 November 2019 |accessdate=}}</ref> Sultana was elected as MP for Coventry South in the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 general election]], with a majority of 401.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/politics/constituencies/E14000651|title=Coventry South|accessdate=17 January 2020|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign, ''[[The Jewish Chronicle]]'' reported that in 2015, while she was a student, Sultana made social media posts from a subsequently deleted account which implied that she would celebrate the deaths of former Labour prime minister [[Tony Blair]], Israeli prime minister [[Benjamin Netanyahu]] and former US president [[George W. Bush]] and she supported \"violent resistance\" by Palestinians.<ref name=JC/> Sultana apologised for the posts and stated that she no longer held those views and \"wrote them out of frustration rather than any malice\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-coventry-warwickshire-50292235|title=Labour Coventry South candidate Zarah Sultana apologises for 'celebrate deaths' post|publisher=BBC News|date=4 November 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/conservative-party/house/house-magazine/108577/class-2019-meet-new-mps|publisher=Politics Home|date=16 December 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020|last=Bond|first=Daniel|title=Class of 2019: Meet the new MPs}}</ref> The Labour Party re-interviewed her as a consequence of the posts, and she remained the candidate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.coventrytelegraph.net/news/coventry-news/coventry-labour-candidate-faces-re-17217042|work=Coventry Telegraph|title=Coventry Labour candidate faces 're-interview' over tweets|date=18 November 2019|accessdate=17 January 2020|last=Stretton|first=Rachel}}</ref> Subsequent to her election, a further social media post made by Sultana in 2015 was reported in which she stated that students supporting [[Zionism]] were \"advocating a racist ideology...champion[ing] a state created through [[ethnic cleansing]] ...[[apartheid]] and [[war crimes]].\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/labour-mp-zarah-sultana-told-jewish-student-privilege-allowed-them-to-argue-peaceful-solution-to-i-1.495607|title=Labour MP Zarah Sultana told student that 'privilege' allowed them to argue for Middle East peace|last=Harpin|first=Lee|date=24 January 2020|work=Jewish Chronicle|accessdate=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn her maiden speech, she decried what she called \"40 years of [[Thatcherism]]\", criticised the government for the effects of [[United Kingdom government austerity programme|austerity]], and voiced her support for a [[Green_New_Deal#In_the_UK|Green New Deal]] to combat climate change.<ref name=Vice>{{cite news|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/7kz8p9/zarah-sultana-mp-labour-maiden-speech-interview|publisher=Vice|title=Zarah Sultana MP: 'When I See Conservatives, I Think About All the Harm They've Caused'|last=Segalov|first=Michael|date=23 January 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://coventryobserver.co.uk/news/sultana-breaks-convention-in-maiden-speech-to-the-commons/|work=Coventry Observer|title=New Coventry MP Sultana, 26, uses first Commons speech to fire broadside for 'my generation'|date=16 January 2020|accessdate=4 February 2020}}</ref> She joined the [[Socialist Campaign Group]] shortly after being elected<ref>{{cite tweet|user=zarahsultana|number=1220108818484539392|title=Proud to be in the Socialist Campaign Group meeting today for its official endorsement of @RLong_Bailey for Leader and @RichardBurgon for Deputy Leader. Now let's get these socialists elected! pic.twitter.com/2wndXTOOyU|date=22 January 2020|accessdate=2 February 2020}}</ref> and in the [[2020 Labour Party leadership election]], nominated [[Rebecca Long-Bailey]] for leader and [[Richard Burgon]] for [[2020 Labour Party deputy leadership election|deputy leader]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/rolling-list-mp-mep-nominations-for-labour-leadership-candidates/|publisher=LabourList|date=8 January 2020|accessdate=17 January 2020|title=Rolling list: MP/MEP nominations for Labour leadership candidates}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://labourlist.org/2020/01/rolling-list-mp-mep-nominations-for-labour-deputy-leadership-candidates/|publisher=LabourList|date=8 January 2020|title=Rolling list: MP/MEP nominations for Labour deputy leadership candidates|accessdate=17 January 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2020, Sultana was appointed as [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Dan Carden]], the [[Shadow Secretary of State for International Development]].<ref>{{cite tweet|user=zarahsultana |number=1222165789165273091 |date=28 January 2020 |title= I'm excited to join the Shadow International Development team, as @DanCardenMP's Parliamentary Private Secretary! The struggle to build a sustainable world for all \u2013 not just the super-rich \u2013 is close to my heart. That's the role Britain should be playing on the global stage.}}</ref> She was removed from this role in a subsequent reshuffle under [[Keir Starmer]]. <ref>https://labourlist.org/2020/04/shadow-ministers-appointed-as-starmer-completes-frontbench/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{UK MP links |parliament=4786 |publicwhip=Zarah_Sultana |theywork=zarah_sultana}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jim Cunningham (politician)|Jim Cunningham]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br />for [[Coventry South (UK Parliament constituency)|Coventry South]]|years=[[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{S-end}}\n{{West Midlands Labour Party MPs}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sultana, Zarah}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1993 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century British women politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Birmingham]]\n[[Category:British politicians of Pakistani descent]]\n[[Category:English Muslims]]\n[[Category:English people of Azad Kashmiri descent]]\n[[Category:English socialists]]\n[[Category:Female members of the Parliament of the United Kingdom for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Members of Parliament for Coventry]]\n[[Category:Muslim socialists]]\n[[Category:People educated at King Edward VI Handsworth]]\n[[Category:People from Birmingham, West Midlands]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParliamentary career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zarah_Sultana"}
{"title_page": "Sandeep Singh", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian field hockey player, politician}}\n{{Other uses}} \n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox field hockey player\n| name               = Sandeep Singh \n| fullname           = \n| image              = Jagbir & Sandeep Singh.jpg\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1986|2|27}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shahabad, Kurukshetra|Shahabad]], [[Haryana]], India\n| height             = {{convert|1.84|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://melbourne2006.com.au/Participants/Participants?ID=105922 |title= CWG Melbourne: Player's Profile |access-date= 15 January 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120424020838/http://melbourne2006.com.au/Participants/Participants?ID=105922 |archive-date= 24 April 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n| weight             = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| website            = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| position           = [[Field hockey#Positions|Fullback]]\n| clubs1             = [[Mumbai Magicians]]\n| years1             = 2013\n| caps1              = 12\n| goals1             = 11\n| clubs2             = [[Punjab Warriors]]\n| years2             = 2014\u20132015\n| caps2              = 1\n| goals2             = 22\n| clubs3             = [[Ranchi Rays]]\n| years3             = 2016\u2013present\n| caps3              = 1\n| goals3             = 0\n| nationalteam1      = [[India men's national field hockey team|India]]\n| nationalyears1     = 2004\u20132012\n| nationalcaps1      = \n| nationalgoals1     = \n| turnedpro          = \n| coach              = \n| retired            = \n| coaching           = \n| updated            = 21 January 2016\n|medaltemplates-expand=yes\n|medaltemplates={{MedalSport | Men's [[Field hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{IND}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2010 Commonwealth Games|2010 New Delhi]]|[[Field hockey at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Hockey Champions Challenge|Champions Challenge]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2007 Men's Hockey Champions Challenge|2007 Belgium]]|Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2009 Men's Sultan Azlan Shah Cup|2009 Malaysia]]|Team}}\n}}\n\n'''Sandeep Singh''' (born 27 February 1986) is an Indian professional [[field hockey]] player from Haryana and an ex-captain of the [[India men's national field hockey team|Indian national team]].<ref name=\"DNA Sandeep Shot in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report_sandeep-singh-named-captain-of-the-hockey-team_1220301|title=Sandeep Singh named captain of the hockey team|date=10 January 2009|publisher=}}</ref> He generally features as a [[Field hockey#Positions|full back]] and is a [[Drag flick|penalty corner specialist]] for the team. He was famous as ''Flicker Singh'' in media. Singh currently holds a [[Deputy superintendent|DSP]] rank in the [[Haryana Police]]. He is also [[Member of parliament|MLA]] of [[Pehowa]] City which is situated in [[Kurukshetra]] from [[Bharatiya Janata Party]].\n\n==Early life==\nSingh hails from [[Shahabad, Kurukshetra|Shahabad]] town in [[Kurukshetra district|Kurukshetra]], Haryana.<ref name=\"Sharma\">{{cite news |last1=Sharma |first1=Jeevan Prakash |title=When the going gets tough\u2026 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/when-the-going-gets-tough/story-cfma41RdjOQJjPRyVWm24N.html |accessdate=10 February 2019 |work=Hindustan Times |date=11 April 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190210231113/https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/when-the-going-gets-tough/story-cfma41RdjOQJjPRyVWm24N.html |archivedate=10 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was educated at [[Shivalik Public School, Mohali]]. He was born to Gurucharan Singh Saini and Daljeet Kaur Saini.<ref name=\"Surname and Community Proof\">{{cite web|url=https://news.webindia123.com/news/Articles/India/20120228/1936911.html}}</ref>. His elder brother, Bikramjeet Singh, is also a field hockey player and plays for Indian Oil.<ref name=\"DNA Sandeep Shot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report_drag-flicker-shot-out-of-wc_1048871|title=Drag-flicker shot out of WC|date=22 August 2006|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===International hockey===\nSandeep's international debut was in January 2004 in [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] in Kuala Lumpur. He took over as the captain of the Indian national team in January 2009, and [[Rajpal Singh]] succeeded him later in 2010. Singh is a well known drag-flicker. At a time he was said to have the best speed in the world in drag flick (speed 145&nbsp;km/h). Under his captaincy, the Indian team managed to clinch the [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] in 2009 after defeating [[Malaysia]] in the finals at [[Ipoh]]. India won the title after a long wait of 13 years. Singh was also the top goal scorer of the Sultan Azlan Shah Cup tournament\n\nThe [[India men's national field hockey team]] have qualified for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London after a gap of 8 years. The team had a resounding victory over [[France men's national field hockey team|France]] in the finals of the Olympic qualifiers by beating France 9\u20131. Ace drag-flicker Singh starred in the final against France by scoring five goals \u2013 including a hat-trick \u2013 all from penalty corners (19th, 26th, 38th, 49th and 51st minutes).<ref name=\"NDTV\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/othersports/hockey/item/186014-hockey-indian-men-qualify-for-olympics-after-8-years?pfrom=home-lateststories|title=Indian Hockey Team Qualifies for London Olympics|publisher=NDTV|date=26 February 2012|accessdate=26 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228233126/http://sports.ndtv.com/othersports/hockey/item/186014-hockey-indian-men-qualify-for-olympics-after-8-years?pfrom=home-lateststories|archive-date=28 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Singh was the highest scorer of the Olympic qualifiers tournament by scoring 16 goals.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Club career===\nSandeep Singh became the fifth highest-paid marquee player at the inaugural [[Hockey India League]] as the Mumbai franchise bought him for US$64,400<ref>{{cite news |title= Hockey India League Auction: the final squads list |url= http://ibnlive.in.com/news/hil-auction-as-the-teams-shape-up/310745-5-136.html |publisher= CNN-IBN |date= 16 December 2012 |accessdate= 13 January 2013}}</ref> with his base price being US$27,800. The Mumbai team has been named [[Mumbai Magicians]]. Scoring 11 goals in 12 games, Singh emerged as the top scorer in the first edition of the league.<ref>{{cite news |title= Sandeep Singh needs to reinvent himself, says coach Michael Nobbs |url= http://sports.ndtv.com/othersports/hockey/item/203392-sandeep-singh-needs-to-reinvent-himself-says-coach-michael-nobbs |publisher= [[NDTV]] |date= 11 February 2013 |accessdate= 15 February 2013}}</ref> In 2014, he was signed by [[Punjab Warriors]]. After playing two seasons for the team, he was signed by [[Ranchi Rays]] for US$81,000 in 2015 starting [[2016 Hockey India League season|2016]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Akashdeep top Indian pick, Sardar a big let down in HIL auction|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/hockey/hero-hockey-india-league-2016-auction/article7662187.ece|accessdate=21 January 2016|work=The Hindu|date=17 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Singh relocated to the UK to play for [[Havant Hockey Club]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.south-league.com/results/league/prem11/2014-2015|title=South Hockey League - Results - Premier - Division 1 - 2014-2015|work=South-league.com|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Shooting incident==\nOn 2 August 2006, Singh was seriously injured after being hit by an accidental gunshot in the ''[[Kalka Shatabdi Express]]'' train, while on his way to join the national team due to leave for the World Cup in Africa two days later. He was almost paralyzed and on the wheelchair for 1 year of his life. He was 20 at that time. Singh not only recovered from that serious injury but also established himself again and played world cup for India in 2010 Indian team.<ref name=\"DNA Sandeep Shot in\" />\n\n==Career achievements==\n* Sandeep Singh scored the most goals and won the Man of the Tournament award in the 2009 [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]].\n* Scoring 16 goals, Singh was the leading goal scorer in the [[Men's field hockey Qualifying Tournaments for the 2012 Summer Olympics|qualifying tournament for the 2012 London Olympics]].<ref name=\"NDTV\"/>\n\n== Awards ==\n* '''2010''': [[Arjuna Award]] recipient for achievements in [[field hockey]]\n\n==Portrayal in film==\nFilmmaker [[Shaad Ali]] has made a biographical film titled ''[[Soorma (film)|Soorma]]'' on Sandeep's life. [[Diljit Dosanjh]] has played Sandeep Singh's role in the film. It was released on 13 July 2018. The film also stars [[Taapsee Pannu]] and [[Angad Bedi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/diljit-dosanjh-as-sandeep-singh-soorma-hockey|title=Diljit Dosanjh as Hockey Legend Sandeep Singh In\"Soorma\"|website=The Quint}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website |http://www.sandeepsingh.co.in}} {{dead link|date=October 2018}}\n{{dead link|date=November 2018}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110225045505/http://www.bharatiyahockey.org/khiladi/2004/sandeep_singh.htm Sandeep Singh's profile on Bhartiya Hockey]\n* http://www.hindu.com/mp/2005/05/12/stories/2005051201250400.htm\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20110721181351/http://sportchannel.in/?p=375\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120228234902/http://sports.ndtv.com/othersports/hockey/item/186015-sandeep-singh-drag-flicker-powers-india-to-the-olympics Sandeep Singh powers India to London Olympics]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Sandeep Singh &ndash; International Tournaments\n | bg        = #0077FF\n | fg        = #FFFF40\n|list1=\n{{India FH Squad 2004 Summer Olympics}}\n{{India FH Squad 2006 Commonwealth Games}}\n{{India FH Squad 2010 Commonwealth Games}}\n{{India FH Squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Sandeep}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players from Haryana]]\n[[Category:People from Kurukshetra district]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2010 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in field hockey]]\n[[Category:World Series Hockey players]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Indian police officers]]\n[[Category:Olympic field hockey players of India]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Indian male field hockey players]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games silver medallists for India]]\n[[Category:Commonwealth Games medallists in field hockey]]\n[[Category:Asian Games bronze medalists for India]]\n[[Category:Hockey India League players]]\n[[Category:Havant Hockey Club players]]\n[[Category:Medalists at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n[[Category:Bharatiya Janata Party politicians from Haryana]]\n[[Category:Haryana MLAs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Members of the Haryana Legislative Assembly]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2006 Commonwealth Games]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian field hockey player, politician}}\n{{Other uses}} \n{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox field hockey player\n| name               = Sandeep Singh \n| fullname           = \n| image              = Jagbir & Sandeep Singh.jpg\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1986|2|27}}\n| birth_place        = [[Shahabad, Kurukshetra|Shahabad]], [[Haryana]], India\n| height             = {{convert|1.84|m|ftin|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web |url= http://melbourne2006.com.au/Participants/Participants?ID=105922 |title= CWG Melbourne: Player's Profile |access-date= 15 January 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120424020838/http://melbourne2006.com.au/Participants/Participants?ID=105922 |archive-date= 24 April 2012 |url-status= dead |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n| weight             = <!-- {{convert|}} (yyyy) -->\n| website            = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| position           = [[Field hockey#Positions|Fullback]]\n| clubs1             = [[Mumbai Magicians]]\n| years1             = 2013\n| caps1              = 12\n| goals1             = 11\n| clubs2             = [[Punjab Warriors]]\n| years2             = 2014\u20132015\n| caps2              = 1\n| goals2             = 22\n| clubs3             = [[Ranchi Rays]]\n| years3             = 2016\u2013present\n| caps3              = 1\n| goals3             = 0\n| nationalteam1      = [[India men's national field hockey team|India]]\n| nationalyears1     = 2004\u20132012\n| nationalcaps1      = \n| nationalgoals1     = \n| turnedpro          = \n| coach              = \n| retired            = \n| coaching           = \n| updated            = 21 January 2016\n|medaltemplates-expand=yes\n|medaltemplates={{MedalSport | Men's [[Field hockey]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | {{IND}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2010 Commonwealth Games|2010 New Delhi]]|[[Field hockey at the 2010 Commonwealth Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Hockey Champions Challenge|Champions Challenge]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2007 Men's Hockey Champions Challenge|2007 Belgium]]|Team}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2009 Men's Sultan Azlan Shah Cup|2009 Malaysia]]|Team}}\n}}\n\n'''Sandeep Singh''' (born 27 February 1986) is an Indian professional [[field hockey]] player from Haryana and an ex-captain of the [[India men's national field hockey team|Indian national team]].<ref name=\"DNA Sandeep Shot in\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report_sandeep-singh-named-captain-of-the-hockey-team_1220301|title=Sandeep Singh named captain of the hockey team|date=10 January 2009|publisher=}}</ref> He generally features as a [[Field hockey#Positions|full back]] and is a [[Drag flick|penalty corner specialist]] for the team. He was famous as ''Flicker Singh'' in media. Singh currently holds a [[Deputy superintendent|DSP]] rank in the [[Haryana Police]]. He is [[Member of parliament|MLA]] of [[Pehowa]] City which is situated in [[Kurukshetra]].\n\n==Early life==\nSingh hails from [[Shahabad, Kurukshetra|Shahabad]] town in [[Kurukshetra district|Kurukshetra]], Haryana.<ref name=\"Sharma\">{{cite news |last1=Sharma |first1=Jeevan Prakash |title=When the going gets tough\u2026 |url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/when-the-going-gets-tough/story-cfma41RdjOQJjPRyVWm24N.html |accessdate=10 February 2019 |work=Hindustan Times |date=11 April 2012 |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20190210231113/https://www.hindustantimes.com/education/when-the-going-gets-tough/story-cfma41RdjOQJjPRyVWm24N.html |archivedate=10 February 2019 |url-status=live  }}</ref> He was educated at [[Shivalik Public School, Mohali]]. He was born to Gurucharan Singh Saini and Daljeet Kaur Saini.<ref name=\"Surname and Community Proof\">{{cite web|url=https://news.webindia123.com/news/Articles/India/20120228/1936911.html}}</ref>. His elder brother, Bikramjeet Singh, is also a field hockey player and plays for Indian Oil.<ref name=\"DNA Sandeep Shot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/sport/report_drag-flicker-shot-out-of-wc_1048871|title=Drag-flicker shot out of WC|date=22 August 2006|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===International hockey===\nSandeep's international debut was in January 2004 in [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] in Kuala Lumpur. He took over as the captain of the Indian national team in January 2009, and [[Rajpal Singh]] succeeded him later in 2010. Singh is a well known drag-flicker. At a time he was said to have the best speed in the world in drag flick (speed 145&nbsp;km/h). Under his captaincy, the Indian team managed to clinch the [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]] in 2009 after defeating [[Malaysia]] in the finals at [[Ipoh]]. India won the title after a long wait of 13 years. Singh was also the top goal scorer of the Sultan Azlan Shah Cup tournament\n\nThe [[India men's national field hockey team]] have qualified for the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in London after a gap of 8 years. The team had a resounding victory over [[France men's national field hockey team|France]] in the finals of the Olympic qualifiers by beating France 9\u20131. Ace drag-flicker Singh starred in the final against France by scoring five goals \u2013 including a hat-trick \u2013 all from penalty corners (19th, 26th, 38th, 49th and 51st minutes).<ref name=\"NDTV\">{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/othersports/hockey/item/186014-hockey-indian-men-qualify-for-olympics-after-8-years?pfrom=home-lateststories|title=Indian Hockey Team Qualifies for London Olympics|publisher=NDTV|date=26 February 2012|accessdate=26 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228233126/http://sports.ndtv.com/othersports/hockey/item/186014-hockey-indian-men-qualify-for-olympics-after-8-years?pfrom=home-lateststories|archive-date=28 February 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> Singh was the highest scorer of the Olympic qualifiers tournament by scoring 16 goals.{{cn|date=October 2019}}\n\n===Club career===\nSandeep Singh became the fifth highest-paid marquee player at the inaugural [[Hockey India League]] as the Mumbai franchise bought him for US$64,400<ref>{{cite news |title= Hockey India League Auction: the final squads list |url= http://ibnlive.in.com/news/hil-auction-as-the-teams-shape-up/310745-5-136.html |publisher= CNN-IBN |date= 16 December 2012 |accessdate= 13 January 2013}}</ref> with his base price being US$27,800. The Mumbai team has been named [[Mumbai Magicians]]. Scoring 11 goals in 12 games, Singh emerged as the top scorer in the first edition of the league.<ref>{{cite news |title= Sandeep Singh needs to reinvent himself, says coach Michael Nobbs |url= http://sports.ndtv.com/othersports/hockey/item/203392-sandeep-singh-needs-to-reinvent-himself-says-coach-michael-nobbs |publisher= [[NDTV]] |date= 11 February 2013 |accessdate= 15 February 2013}}</ref> In 2014, he was signed by [[Punjab Warriors]]. After playing two seasons for the team, he was signed by [[Ranchi Rays]] for US$81,000 in 2015 starting [[2016 Hockey India League season|2016]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Akashdeep top Indian pick, Sardar a big let down in HIL auction|url=http://www.thehindu.com/sport/hockey/hero-hockey-india-league-2016-auction/article7662187.ece|accessdate=21 January 2016|work=The Hindu|date=17 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Singh relocated to the UK to play for [[Havant Hockey Club]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.south-league.com/results/league/prem11/2014-2015|title=South Hockey League - Results - Premier - Division 1 - 2014-2015|work=South-league.com|accessdate=21 December 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Shooting incident==\nOn 2 August 2006, Singh was seriously injured after being hit by an accidental gunshot in the ''[[Kalka Shatabdi Express]]'' train, while on his way to join the national team due to leave for the World Cup in Africa two days later. He was almost paralyzed and on the wheelchair for 1 year of his life. He was 20 at that time. Singh not only recovered from that serious injury but also established himself again and played world cup for India in 2010 Indian team.<ref name=\"DNA Sandeep Shot in\" />\n\n==Career achievements==\n* Sandeep Singh scored the most goals and won the Man of the Tournament award in the 2009 [[Sultan Azlan Shah Cup]].\n* Scoring 16 goals, Singh was the leading goal scorer in the [[Men's field hockey Qualifying Tournaments for the 2012 Summer Olympics|qualifying tournament for the 2012 London Olympics]].<ref name=\"NDTV\"/>\n\n== Awards ==\n* '''2010''': [[Arjuna Award]] recipient for achievements in [[field hockey]]\n\n==Portrayal in film==\nFilmmaker [[Shaad Ali]] has made a biographical film titled ''[[Soorma (film)|Soorma]]'' on Sandeep's life. [[Diljit Dosanjh]] has played Sandeep Singh's role in the film. It was released on 13 July 2018. The film also stars [[Taapsee Pannu]] and [[Angad Bedi]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/entertainment/diljit-dosanjh-as-sandeep-singh-soorma-hockey|title=Diljit Dosanjh as Hockey Legend Sandeep Singh In\"Soorma\"|website=The Quint}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website |http://www.sandeepsingh.co.in}} {{dead link|date=October 2018}}\n{{dead link|date=November 2018}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110225045505/http://www.bharatiyahockey.org/khiladi/2004/sandeep_singh.htm Sandeep Singh's profile on Bhartiya Hockey]\n* http://www.hindu.com/mp/2005/05/12/stories/2005051201250400.htm\n* https://web.archive.org/web/20110721181351/http://sportchannel.in/?p=375\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120228234902/http://sports.ndtv.com/othersports/hockey/item/186015-sandeep-singh-drag-flicker-powers-india-to-the-olympics Sandeep Singh powers India to London Olympics]\n\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Sandeep Singh &ndash; International Tournaments\n | bg        = #0077FF\n | fg        = #FFFF40\n|list1=\n{{India FH Squad 2004 Summer Olympics}}\n{{India FH Squad 2006 Commonwealth Games}}\n{{India FH Squad 2010 Commonwealth Games}}\n{{India FH Squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Singh, Sandeep}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players from Haryana]]\n[[Category:People from Kurukshetra district]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2010 Commonwealth Games]]\n[[Category:Asian Games medalists in field hockey]]\n[[Category:World Series Hockey players]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2004 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2012 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:Indian police officers]]\n[[Category:Olympic field hockey players of India]]\n[[Category:Field hockey players at the 2010 Asian Games]]\n[[Category